I think a problem with "microdoses" of LSD is that even if they are biologically sound, the cultural image of LSD as a "psychedelic drug" is still strong enough to demonize the effect and taint it in a way. People should think of it as an anti-allergenic dose of Benadryl instead.

I believe the Deleuze philosopher describes this in one of the books, but even innocent experiences can be corrupted pretty easily if they are placed in a paradigm of sinfulness. If the person taking it has this stereotype of "trippy creativity inspiration" even a Placebo is bad.
I guess just seeing it as something very ordinary like Tylenol and treating the hallucinations from higher doses as a toxic side effect unrelated to any benefit

E.g. lots of common medical drugs and even spices could make you hallucinate if you accidentally overdosed them, but they don't have this New Age cultural "psychedelic cult" around them. The stereotypical "expectations" are probably more dangerous than the pharmacological effects
